text: To me they completely missed the point of slenderman. The scary part about him isn't that he is a tall man, or that he grabs people with tentacles, its the fact that he just appears. Silently. With no warning. And the longer you look, the deeper into your mind he gets, until you have no control. At that point he either takes you, or enslaves you with his tentacles. His face and body are not ever supposed to move. Only the tentacles.  They are portraying him like any other old boogeyman, which is a disservice. If you are going to make a unique creepy icon, at least do it right

text: Slenderman is the woods, in the dark of the night, trying to escape something you‚Äôre not sure exists. Slenderman is your trusty flashlight, the only tool at your disposal. It should make you feel safe but ultimately you know it can‚Äôt. Slenderman is the eight pages, a story that is only hinted at through the scribbling of a child. A story that is likely much more than it seems. Slenderman is the camera, filming the thing that you‚Äôve been warned not to film. But you still do anyways. Slenderman is the static, the confirmation of the monster hunting you. You realize now that there is NO ESCAPE. But most importantly, Slenderman embodies the fear of something you can‚Äôt see but you KNOW is there.  This ISN‚ÄôT Slenderman.

text: My Problem with "What" this Movie is trying to sell me on is: Explaining the Slenderman Best Answer: Don't. Or At Least, Stop it with the "Google Ex Machina" ~A Movie about Slenderman Entering the Lives of Unsuspecting Victims: I'm All for That! A Movie where the "Monster" Slowly Breaks Apart the Attachments & Minds of his Victims for an Unknown, Unexplained result, Sounds Interesting to me.   Slenderman's Motive, as well as his type of Victim{Children, Teens, Adults, etc}, is Never a Consistent thing{Mainly Because Creppypasta is Written by Different Types of People with Different Ideas}; SO, Have FUN with that. A "Horror Monster" who's MO isn't revealed til the end, and/or Changes depending on Victim, is a Great Idea when considering the ability to tell Many Stories, and Thus Many Movies to make Money from. However, By explaining Him as this "Demon you have to summon for him to Haunt you" seems redundant & silly. If they where to make a sequel(s), What then? Have a different group of People "summon" him & have him do the Same thing? Then What's the Point? A Slenderman Movie, in my Option, Should NEVER be ABOUT the Slenderman; but rather, The Lives of the People he Enters, and the Result of doing so.  For Example: A Man, Celebrating his Promotion at Work by going for a Drive in his Car, Suddenly sees "a Man" in the Middle of the Road. He makes a hard Turn not to hit "him", only for him to Crash into a Tree. As the man looks back, there was no one was on the Road with him. As he goes about his Daily life, Now without his Main motive of transportation, He Starts to Notice someone "Watching Him" on the Bus. When he Looks back, no one is There. The Man starts to think he's going Crazy; He get Careless at work, Yelled at by his boss. He Starts to Lose Sleep, Paranoid of every Noise coming from his house. He Starts to Question if he ever actually Saw "the Man" on the Road. If there was actually someone "Watching him" on the Bus. He Relaxes. Gets a Good Night Sleep, and does so well, His Boss Praises his Work. All's fine, until he see "That Man" Across the Street. Standing there, head down. Not looking at anything but the Ground below him. A Tall man, bald, pale skin, wearing a Suit. The Man, Enraged, Walks towards the "Man" whom He now Knows he saw on the Road. The "Man" That Was "Watching him" on the Bus. The "Man" who was keeping him Awake at Night; he was Ready to confront him... When, at that exact moment: his new form of Transportation, the Bus, came to a Crashing stop, and the Man's world went dark. Waking up in a Hospital bed, he was now hooked up to a Life Support Device. Looking around, there was No one... Except "The Man". He Tried to Scream for help, but couldn't. The "Man" walked up to the Device; The "Man" who did nothing but Enter his life, Now decides what happens next...  No Need to Explain What Slenderman is; Just: What he can do; and the Result from it. The Literal Example of:        Show, Don't Tell!  I'm also Hating how "Google" always has an Answer to the Problem, in Modern Movies. I get it, In the Modern Age: that's the "Go To" Answer for Any Problem. "Just Google it". But, Here's an Idea: What if they do so, and Don't get Results; or, What if it's set in a Time when there is no Internet, what then? Being Powerless, or Having No Answer/Idea to the Threat that comes knocking on your door is a Classic way to Provoke a tension of Fear, without the Need of any Jump Scares. Many People Complain that Slenderman is "Just a Guy, without a Face, coming to Get Ya"; and don't think that's Scary. Fine, perfectly acceptable. But what if you didn't know what he was. What if he Started out as some guy that Followed you Home, or was in your House without any possible way of doing so. What then? You Google it, but only fine Ransional Explainations. "You Left a Window Unlocked", "he was Hiding in your Attic/Basement". So you bolt the Windows & Doors. You make it so there's is no Way anyone could enter your home. Then, You Wake up to see the Slenderman in the Corner of your Room. You get up, and he's gone. You "Google it" again, you get stories, but nothing Concrete... No solution to "Dealing with him"... What then? Exactly. ~Slenderman is the Perfect Kind of "Horror Monster" to HAVE FUN with. You don't need to Explain what he is, that takes away from the Fear. Just Put him in the Life of Any One Person, and go from there.   but, that's Just me. Other people probably have different opinions and ideas about the Slenderman...

text: Hey Sony! I know how to make this movie better, and I haven't seen it yet! Because I know how you're going to screw it up! You're going to explain everything to the audience through poorly delivered dialogue and needless exposition! Your characters are all going to be wiki-dumps on the audience, and that's the exact opposite of what this movie needs! Slender man, needs to be quiet. No explanations, no exposition, no answers. All you need to do is edit the film to remove as much of this junk as you can before it's released! There's clearly so much goodness going into this thing... All you need to do is remove the typical Hollywood garbage that will Strangle it in its cradle. I'm begging you guys! BAM! Masterpiece! You're welcome!
author: Cerebral Static

text: The biggest problem with this movie is the same as always. Slender Man is an inherently Lovecraftian Horror creature, so the story surrounding it should be told from that angle. But as usual, studios will happily take from Lovecraftian imagery, and then immediately rob it of any value. "Show the monster!" "Explain the monster!" And the worst offense... "Defeat the monster!" You Hollywood guys have been pumping out this horror-soup for decades now! Haven't you learned?

text: Really? So they watch a video and Slender Man goes after them? Look i understand taking liberties but that trope shipped SIXTEEN YEARS AGO with The Ring. I am hopeful but you could have simply focused on the friends looking for Katie that goes missing thinking she needs help psychologically, and as they do they learn about Slender Man who begins to stalk them as they realize that he is real. As the film goes on each one goes crazy like Slender drives his victums and one by one each goes missing becoming and it not only becomes a search for Katie but a fight for survival. Then by the end of the film all of them are missing, Slender Man wins.  Now i have a feeling all i described is going to go a roughly similar way but the difference here is no stupid video marks Slender Mans victims. Thats The Ring! Also as the trailer eludes to whoever watches the video is marked it takes away the mystery of how and why Slender Man takes them. You dont need to put or show a reason why he does it the fact you dont know why is what makes it more terrifying.  The three bell tolls is new but in all honesty its pointless. Why have it there? They accept his invitation? Doesn't that mean they are deliberately endangering their lives still? I guess i am going to have to find that out in the theater.  After all i said who knows the film could be good and Slender DOES look great. However i have the suspicion that its going to end up being the GAME (Arrival) had a better story than this.  I am going to see it but when i go into see it i am not going to have the most high of expectations.

text: Looks like an awesome horror film.  One thing I think people miss out on, despite the terrible tragedy of delusional teens killing a girl, is that the description given to slender man, all black with a white face is very old. Sleep paralysis victims often describe something similar.  And I‚Äôm not suggesting he real. It‚Äôs fantasy and fake. But hallucinating and sleep paralysis are fairly common.   When you dream your mind creates entire worlds and species from normal to fictional. Entire cities full of moving people and ect.. all the things you dreams your Brain allowed you to see it and hear it. That can bleed over into reality and consciousness.  It‚Äôs still fake but can seem real.  The whole all black with a  white face monster is fairly normal thing.

text: Just watched the film, aaaaaand it was terrible. I‚Äôm tired of watching horror films where people don‚Äôt react the way I would react to the situations they‚Äôre in. If i saw a ghost, demon, even the slender man, I would run towards the fucker and stop it from harming me first. Many years ago when I believed in demons and ghosts, I woke up to find what looked like a tall pitch black figure standing in the corner of my room, I got out of bed and stood there telling it to fucking try me and walked towards it, turns out it was my imagination like all sightings are. The point I‚Äôm tryna make is that these people in the movies  never fight back when faced with a supernatural entity, I would, because if they were real, we are clearly more powerful than they are. So why be scared of something that A is not real, and B if was real, is weak compared to a human. If you wanna make a movie, make it realistic, it‚Äôs not hard to make a ghost movie that is actually close to what could be real.
